    "4037114": {
      "title": "Dietary alpha-linolenic acid increases the n-3 PUFA content of sow's milk and the tissues of the suckling piglet",
      "abstract": "╬▒-Linolenic acid (18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3) is a precursor to DHA (22ŌłČ6nŌłÆ3), which is essential for normal growth and development in the infant. This study was undertaken to assess how a raised 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 intake in sows affects the nŌłÆ3 PUFA content of the suckling piglet. Sows consumed a high- 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 or control diet (nŌłÆ3 PUFA/nŌłÆ6 PUFA, 0.5 vs. 0.05, respectively) for 10 d prior to parturition and for 14 d postpartum. Piglets suckled from their mothers until 14 d of age, when they were sacrificed. Sows consuming the high-18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 diet had 141% more 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 and 86% more 22ŌłČ6nŌłÆ3 in their milk compared to control sows. There was no difference in the proximate composition of the piglets. The nŌłÆ3/nŌłÆ6 PUFA ratio was 82% higher in the milk of sows consuming the high-18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 diet compared to controls. Piglets suckling from sows consuming the high-18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 die had 423% more 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 in the carcass as well as a 460% higher nŌłÆ3/nŌłÆ6 PUFA ratio than controls. The piglets suckling from sows consuming the high-18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 diet had 333% more 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 and 54% more 22ŌłČ6nŌłÆ3 in the liver, as well as a 114% higher nŌłÆ3/nŌłÆ6 ratio than control piglets. Piglets suckling from sows consuming a high-18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 diet also had 24% more 22ŌłČ6nŌłÆ3 and a 33% higher nŌłÆ3/nŌłÆ6 ratio in the brain compared to control piglets. A high 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 intake in the sow increases not only the 18ŌłČ3nŌłÆ3 but also the 22ŌłČ6nŌłÆ3 content of sow's milk and the tissues of the suckling piglet."
    }
